    <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
      <h2>What is Feline Diabetes?</h2>
      <p>Feline diabetes mellitus occurs when the pancreas can no longer produce enough insulin, or when the body stops responding to insulin effectively. Without insulin, cells can't absorb glucose from the blood — leading to high blood sugar and a cascade of complications.</p>
      <p>Most cats have Type 2 diabetes, which is linked to obesity, inactivity, and diet. Unlike dogs, cats can sometimes go into diabetic remission if caught early and managed aggressively with diet and insulin. That possibility makes early intervention especially important.</p>
      <p>Minou had both diabetes and CKD — managing them together is its own challenge, because some approaches that help one condition can complicate the other.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>US and Canada note:</strong> Common insulins used in cats include Lantus (glargine), Levemir (detemir), and ProZinc. Glargine is widely considered the best option for achieving remission in cats. Confirm with your vet which insulin is appropriate — this is an area where the specific type matters significantly.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="signs" class="content-section">
      <h2>Signs to Watch For</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Dramatically increased thirst and urination</li>
        <li>Weight loss despite normal or increased appetite</li>
        <li>Lethargy, reduced activity</li>
        <li>A plantigrade stance — walking on the hocks rather than the toes (nerve damage from prolonged high blood sugar)</li>
        <li>Vomiting, poor coat condition</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Hypoglycaemia (low blood sugar) is a medical emergency.</strong> Signs include weakness, wobbling, seizures, and unresponsiveness. If you suspect a hypoglycaemic episode, rub corn syrup or honey on the gums immediately and go to an emergency vet.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="management" class="content-section">
      <h2>Day-to-Day Management</h2>
      <p>Managing a diabetic cat means building a routine around consistent mealtimes, regular insulin dosing, and blood glucose monitoring. Home glucose testing — with a small glucometer and lancets — allows you to adjust dosing and catch problems early. Many owners become very capable at this with practice.</p>
      <h3>Diet</h3>
      <p>A high-protein, low-carbohydrate wet food diet is the most evidence-backed dietary approach for feline diabetes. Carbohydrates drive blood sugar spikes — reducing them can significantly improve glucose control and in some cases support remission. Dry food is generally a poor choice for diabetic cats.</p>
      <h3>Glucose curves</h3>
      <p>A glucose curve — measuring blood sugar at intervals over 12 hours — shows how your cat is responding to insulin throughout the day. Your vet can perform one in-clinic, or you can learn to do home curves, which are often more accurate because your cat is less stressed.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>Which insulin are we using, and is glargine an option for my cat?</li>
        <li>What is the target blood glucose range, and when should I be concerned?</li>
        <li>Can I learn to do home glucose curves?</li>
        <li>Is my cat a candidate for remission, and what would that require?</li>
        <li>How does my cat's diet need to change, and what brands do you recommend?</li>
        <li>What are the signs of hypoglycaemia and what should I do if it happens?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

